fields.description:

fields.name: Bouldering The Gorilla's Nest (aka No Fear No Sorrow)
fields.author: Kyle O'Meara
fields.embed: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/134894423?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0&badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0&app_id=137790" width="720" height="1280" frameborder="0" title="Bouldering The Gorilla's Nest (aka No Fear No Sorrow)" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
fields.description: Spectacular boulder problem in Gold Bar Washington with a crazy staired landing. Years ago, a tree fell in front of this giant block that enabled some motivated climbers to use the fallen tree as a foundation for a radical landing platform. From the ground, roughly 9 ft below the landing, you end up actually climbing up through a large hole in the stack of sticks and logs before getting over the platform where you climb up to a very airy and committing finish. One of the best I've ever climbed in those woods!!

fields.description:
In 2017, the Washington Climbers Coalition launched the Washington Climbing Conservation Initiative (WCCI) as a regional stewardship program to address the increasing impacts of growing climbing use at cherished climbing areas across the state. Together with Access Fund Conservation Team West and state land agencies, the initiative has executed 11 weeks of professional trail work at crags and bouldering areas across the state. As of the end of 2017, the initiative had engaged 290 volunteers in over 2,300 hours of work at four locations: Gold Bar, Exit 38 Farside, Index, and Tieton Canyon.

This initiative was made possible by a generous grant from REI with matching funds from WCC, the Seattle Bouldering Project, and individual donors.

Big thanks to the following supporting partners: Cascade Designs, Outdoor Research, Edgeworks, the Mountaineers, Mountains to Sound Greenway Trust, Stone Gardens, Vertical World, American Alpine Club, The North Face, Washington Alpine Club, DNR, WDFW, and State Parks.

Video by Ben Neilson  www.benneilsonmedia.com

fields.description:
Obesity Direct is an overhung problem set on Fraggle Rock in the Clear Cut bouldering area of Gold Bar, Washington.  I have been working it on and off for a few year.  In truth it has been my nemeses.  This video catalogs some of those experiences.  
Thanks to all of you who made the hike up with me, those days have been some of best days out.  And a special shout out to Derek and Erin, good times.

fields.description:
We spent just over a week climbing in the Leavenworth, Washington area, most of it bouldering.  Leavenworth is a pretty awesome bouldering destination, with a high percentage of excellent problems.

The town itself is also quite interesting, themed in a Bavarian style.  As we were there towards the end of September, Oktoberfest celebrations were just getting into full swing.

Problems included are:
The Break V2
420 Slab V0
Sunny and Steep V2
The Real Thing V4
The Pocket V4
Drugstore Cowboy V3

fields.name: Bolder Bouldering
fields.author: WWU-Digital Media in Journalism
fields.embed: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/293145811?title=0&byline=0&portrait=0&badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0&app_id=137790" width="1310" height="720" frameborder="0" title="Bolder Bouldering" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
fields.description:
In a day and age when more and more rock climbers are focusing on the competition and athleticism of indoor climbing gyms, Owen Massey seeks solitude and aesthetic movement among the granite boulders of Washington state.

Western student and Leavenworth, Washington, local, Massey speaks to the philosophy and motivation behind his pursuit of bouldering, an un-roped form of rock climbing emphasizing difficulty of movement close to the ground. 

This video was shot and edited by Western visual journalism student Matthew Tangeman for the spring 2018 digital media course.
